  {# ── Section 1: Why standard labs miss the point ────────────────────────── #}

  <div class="guide-section">
    <div class="guide-section-label">Section 01</div>
    <h2>Why your annual bloodwork<br>isn't telling you the full story</h2>

    <p>Every year, millions of people get a standard blood panel. Their doctor reviews it, says everything looks "normal," and sends them home. But <strong>normal and optimal are not the same thing.</strong></p>

    <p>Standard reference ranges are built from population averages — they're designed to catch disease, not to optimize for a long, healthy life. A cholesterol result that falls within the reference range might still double your lifetime cardiovascular risk. A testosterone level labeled "normal" for your age might be a third of what's associated with the lowest all-cause mortality.</p>

    <div class="guide-problem-box">
      <strong>The gap between "not sick" and "aging optimally" is enormous.</strong> The biomarkers in this guide are the ones that predict how fast you're aging — not whether you have a diagnosable condition right now. Most of them aren't included in a standard CBC or metabolic panel. Most doctors won't order them unless you ask.
    </div>

    <p>This guide closes that gap. Each section covers one biomarker: what it is, why it matters for longevity specifically, what the research says about optimal levels, and how to get tested without a doctor's referral.</p>
  </div>

