  {# ── Section 2: The 10 biomarkers ──────────────────────────────────────── #}

  <div class="guide-section">
    <div class="guide-section-label">Section 02</div>
    <h2>The 10 biomarkers that predict<br>how fast you're aging</h2>

    <p>These aren't the only markers worth tracking. But if you had to build a longevity panel from scratch — the minimum set with maximum signal — this is it. Each one is measurable, modifiable, and strongly linked to all-cause mortality, cardiovascular risk, or biological age in the research literature.</p>

    <div class="guide-markers">

      <div class="guide-marker">
        <div class="guide-marker-left">
          <div class="guide-marker-num">Marker 01</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-name">ApoB</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-aka">Apolipoprotein B</div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-marker-right">
          <p class="guide-marker-why">The most accurate measure of cardiovascular risk available. ApoB counts every atherogenic particle in your blood — including LDL, VLDL, and IDL — giving a precise read on arterial plaque burden that standard LDL cholesterol systematically underestimates. Elevated lifetime ApoB exposure is one of the leading modifiable causes of preventable death.</p>
          <div class="guide-marker-range">
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Standard range</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val standard">&lt; 130 mg/dL</span>
            </div>
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Longevity target</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val">&lt; 60 mg/dL</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="/biomarkers/apob" class="guide-marker-link">Full ApoB guide &#8594;</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="guide-marker">
        <div class="guide-marker-left">
          <div class="guide-marker-num">Marker 02</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-name">hsCRP</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-aka">High-Sensitivity C-Reactive Protein</div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-marker-right">
          <p class="guide-marker-why">The primary blood marker of systemic inflammation — the "slow burn" process that drives cardiovascular disease, cancer, neurodegeneration, and accelerated aging. Unlike standard CRP, the high-sensitivity assay can detect low-grade inflammation years before symptoms appear. Chronic elevation above 1 mg/L is a meaningful signal even when everything else looks normal.</p>
          <div class="guide-marker-range">
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Standard range</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val standard">&lt; 10 mg/L</span>
            </div>
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Longevity target</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val">&lt; 0.7 mg/L</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="/biomarkers/hscrp" class="guide-marker-link">Full hsCRP guide &#8594;</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="guide-marker">
        <div class="guide-marker-left">
          <div class="guide-marker-num">Marker 03</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-name">HbA1c</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-aka">Glycated Hemoglobin</div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-marker-right">
          <p class="guide-marker-why">A 90-day average of blood glucose levels. HbA1c captures what fasting glucose misses — the cumulative glycemic burden across your diet, stress levels, and sleep quality. Even levels at the "high normal" end of the standard range are associated with accelerated brain aging, kidney decline, and cardiovascular risk. The longevity-optimal zone is substantially tighter than clinical cutoffs.</p>
          <div class="guide-marker-range">
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Standard range</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val standard">4.0–5.6%</span>
            </div>
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Longevity target</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val">4.8–5.2%</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="/biomarkers/hba1c" class="guide-marker-link">Full HbA1c guide &#8594;</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="guide-marker">
        <div class="guide-marker-left">
          <div class="guide-marker-num">Marker 04</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-name">Fasting Insulin</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-aka">Serum Insulin</div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-marker-right">
          <p class="guide-marker-why">The earliest detectable signal of insulin resistance — often elevated for a decade before HbA1c or fasting glucose shifts. High fasting insulin drives fat storage, accelerates arterial aging, elevates cancer risk, and is one of the strongest predictors of metabolic disease progression. Not included in standard panels. Not ordered by most physicians. One of the highest-value tests you can add.</p>
          <div class="guide-marker-range">
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Standard range</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val standard">2–25 uIU/mL</span>
            </div>
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Longevity target</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val">&lt; 6 uIU/mL</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="/biomarkers/fasting-insulin" class="guide-marker-link">Full Fasting Insulin guide &#8594;</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="guide-marker">
        <div class="guide-marker-left">
          <div class="guide-marker-num">Marker 05</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-name">Vitamin D</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-aka">25-Hydroxy Vitamin D</div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-marker-right">
          <p class="guide-marker-why">A pro-hormone active in virtually every tissue in the body. Deficiency — defined as below 30 ng/mL by most labs — is associated with cardiovascular disease, cancer, autoimmune dysfunction, accelerated bone loss, and all-cause mortality. Roughly 40% of adults are deficient. The longevity-optimal zone is substantially higher than the clinical floor, and maintaining it requires deliberate year-round attention.</p>
          <div class="guide-marker-range">
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Standard range</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val standard">30–100 ng/mL</span>
            </div>
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Longevity target</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val">50–70 ng/mL</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="/biomarkers/vitamin-d" class="guide-marker-link">Full Vitamin D guide &#8594;</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="guide-marker">
        <div class="guide-marker-left">
          <div class="guide-marker-num">Marker 06</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-name">Homocysteine</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-aka">Total Plasma Homocysteine</div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-marker-right">
          <p class="guide-marker-why">An amino acid byproduct of methionine metabolism. Elevated homocysteine is a direct vascular toxin — it damages arterial walls, promotes clotting, accelerates cognitive decline, and is an independent risk factor for cardiovascular disease and dementia. It's primarily driven by B vitamin status (B12, folate, B6) and is highly correctable. Routinely missed because it's not part of standard panels.</p>
          <div class="guide-marker-range">
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Standard range</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val standard">&lt; 15 µmol/L</span>
            </div>
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Longevity target</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val">&lt; 7 µmol/L</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="/biomarkers/homocysteine" class="guide-marker-link">Full Homocysteine guide &#8594;</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="guide-marker">
        <div class="guide-marker-left">
          <div class="guide-marker-num">Marker 07</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-name">Testosterone</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-aka">Total Testosterone</div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-marker-right">
          <p class="guide-marker-why">Far more than a sex hormone — testosterone regulates muscle mass, bone density, metabolic rate, cognitive function, red blood cell production, and cardiovascular health in both men and women. Levels decline with age, but the rate of decline is highly modifiable. Low testosterone is associated with metabolic syndrome, depression, cognitive decline, and increased all-cause mortality. Most doctors treat anything within the broad normal range as fine — it isn't.</p>
          <div class="guide-marker-range">
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Standard range (men)</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val standard">264–916 ng/dL</span>
            </div>
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Longevity target (men)</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val">600–900 ng/dL</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="/biomarkers/testosterone" class="guide-marker-link">Full Testosterone guide &#8594;</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="guide-marker">
        <div class="guide-marker-left">
          <div class="guide-marker-num">Marker 08</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-name">IGF-1</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-aka">Insulin-Like Growth Factor 1</div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-marker-right">
          <p class="guide-marker-why">The primary mediator of growth hormone signaling — governing cellular repair, muscle and bone maintenance, and metabolic function. Both too low and too high IGF-1 are associated with increased mortality, making it one of the few biomarkers with a narrow longevity-optimal zone rather than a simple directional target. Declines sharply with age, poor sleep, and nutrient deficiency. A key marker of biological aging rate.</p>
          <div class="guide-marker-range">
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Standard range</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val standard">53–331 ng/mL</span>
            </div>
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Longevity target</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val">120–180 ng/mL</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="/biomarkers/igf-1" class="guide-marker-link">Full IGF-1 guide &#8594;</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="guide-marker">
        <div class="guide-marker-left">
          <div class="guide-marker-num">Marker 09</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-name">Lp(a)</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-aka">Lipoprotein(a)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-marker-right">
          <p class="guide-marker-why">A genetically determined lipoprotein particle that accelerates atherosclerosis, promotes clotting, and is one of the strongest independent risk factors for cardiovascular disease and stroke. Elevated Lp(a) affects roughly 20% of the population — and most of them have no idea. It's largely unresponsive to diet and lifestyle, making it a critical piece of baseline risk information. Everyone should know their number.</p>
          <div class="guide-marker-range">
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Standard range</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val standard">&lt; 75 nmol/L</span>
            </div>
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Longevity target</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val">&lt; 30 nmol/L</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="/biomarkers/lipoprotein-a" class="guide-marker-link">Full Lp(a) guide &#8594;</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="guide-marker">
        <div class="guide-marker-left">
          <div class="guide-marker-num">Marker 10</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-name">Omega-3 Index</div>
          <div class="guide-marker-aka">EPA + DHA %</div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-marker-right">
          <p class="guide-marker-why">The percentage of EPA and DHA in red blood cell membranes — a reliable 3-month average of omega-3 status. A low Omega-3 Index is one of the most prevalent and correctable cardiovascular risk factors, associated with elevated triglycerides, inflammation, cardiac arrhythmia, and all-cause mortality. Most people eating a Western diet score between 4–6%; the longevity-optimal zone starts at 8%. Correctable with supplementation in 3–4 months.</p>
          <div class="guide-marker-range">
            <div class="guide-range-item">
              <span class="guide-range-label">Standard range</span>
              <span class="guide-range-val standard">&gt; 4%</span>
